Introduction¶

Tip: In this section of the report, provide a brief introduction to the dataset you've selected for analysis. At the end of this section, describe the questions that you plan on exploring over the course of the report. Try to build your report around the analysis of at least one dependent variable and three independent variables.

Data on primary, secondary, tertiary education expenditure per capita, and GDP per capita were acquired from Gapminder website in the form of csv files. The education expenditure per capita is the government expenditure per student for the given level of education. The outcome of the analysis would be to get an understanding on variation of GDP for OECD countries. Also to understand the variation in expenditures on different level of education expressed as a percentage GDP per capita by country. The final question would be to find out if education expenditure is dependent on the GDP or vice versa.

Inferences from above plots¶

  1. In terms of primary and secondary education Sweden and Italy consistently spent more, however for tertiary education Afghanistan spent more by a significant margin.
  2. It should be noted that the tertiary eduction expenditure plot for Afghanistan is constant which signifies only a year value is reported. It signifies the limitation of subsituting NA's with average values. Therefore, it would be improper to conclude on the country's expenditure based on the given data.
  3. Sweden is a better GDP per capita performer when compared to Italy. What is interesting is that around year 2000 and onward, the growth rate of Italy has reduced to negtive numbers and that has impacted education expenditure specifically primary and secondary where it crosses line with Sweden.
  4. Another interesting pattern could be noted in variation of GDP growth rate of Afghanistan. The variaton rate is extremely volatile as compared to its counterparts. It could attributed to the amount of financial aid Afghanistan receives. We will test this hypothesis in the next section.

#In the earlier plot the line colors are cycled which is making it difficult to differentiate b/w 
#different countries. Hence we take help of the line type.

from itertools import cycle
lines = ["-","--","-.",":"]
linecycler = cycle(lines)

ax=plt.figure(figsize=(15,15)).gca()
for i in oecd:
    y_gdp= df_gdp_p_cap_yrl_v2.loc[i]
    plt.plot(x,y_gdp, next(linecycler), label = i)

ax.legend(loc= 'center right', bbox_to_anchor= (1.15, 0.5))
ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(MaxNLocator(integer=True))
plt.title('gdp per capita', fontsize= 16)
plt.xlabel('years');

We can see on the above plot that almost all countries faced a sharp decline in GDP per capita around the period of 2007-2008. Our hypothesis in the previous section of a global phenomenon affecting the countries is justified. This could be attributed to the global recession that occurred during the period.

#education expenditure of countries
#country='Norway'

def plot_data (country):
    x1= list(range(1995, 2014))
    y1= df_gdp_p_cap_yrl_v2.loc[country]
    y2= df_pr_ed_v2.loc[country]
    y3= df_se_ed_v2.loc[country]
    y4= df_te_ed_v2.loc[country]
    ax=plt.figure(figsize=(10,10)).gca()
    plt.title(country, fontsize= 16)
    plt.plot(x1, y1, label= 'GDP per capita')
    plt.plot(x1, y2, label= 'exp. per capita in primary education')
    plt.plot(x1, y3, label= 'exp. per capita in secondary education')
    plt.plot(x1, y4, label= 'exp. per capita in tertiary education')
    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(MaxNLocator(integer=True))
    ax.legend(loc= 'center right', bbox_to_anchor= (1.45, 0.5))
    plt.show()
In [82]:
plot_data('Ireland'); plot_data('United Kingdom')

From the above charts the expenditure doesn't seem to be correlated to the GDP. For example, in the case of 2 countries plotted above--Ireland and United Kingdom, the expenditure on education went up with slowing economy in the former case but in the latter its almost opposite. However, it would be improper to conclude on a correlation through observing visually. A correlation coefficient on the values could shed more light on the dependencies.

Conclusions¶

Datasets representing different indicators of countries across the globe are replete with null values and it is important to clean up or ammend these values to get sensible results.Once the shapes and the values of the datasets are consistent then the plots of datasets could reveal interesting trends as we saw in the case of economies affected by recession. However, sometimes it is difficult to answer some questions through visual plots only. For instance, in case of correlation between aid and GDP growth, correlation b/w GDP growth and education expenditure could not be judged through plots rather, a correlation coefficient is needed.
